  "prompt": "What causes fluttering eyes?",
  "response": "Fluttering eyes, often referred to as eye twitching or myokymia, can be caused by a variety of factors. Here are some common causes:\n\n1. **Stress and Fatigue**: High levels of stress or fatigue are common triggers for eye twitching. The body's response to stress can manifest in various ways, including involuntary muscle contractions.\n\n2. **Caffeine and Alcohol**: Excessive consumption of caffeine or alcohol can lead to dehydration and stimulate the nervous system, which may result in eye twitching.\n\n3. **Eye Strain**: Prolonged use of digital devices, reading for long periods, or other activities that strain the eyes can cause twitching. This is often referred to as digital eye strain or computer vision syndrome.\n\n4. **Dry Eyes**: Insufficient lubrication of the eyes can lead to irritation and twitching. Dry eyes can be caused by various factors, including aging, certain medications, and environmental conditions.\n\n5. **Nutritional Deficiencies**: A lack of essential nutrients, particularly magnesium, can lead to muscle spasms, including eye twitching.\n\n6. **Allergies**: Allergic reactions can cause irritation and twitching of the eyelids. Rubbing the eyes due to itching can exacerbate the condition.\n\n7. **Medications**: Some medications, particularly those that affect the nervous system, can cause eye twitching as a side effect.\n\n8. **Eye Irritation**: Any form of irritation, such as from foreign objects, smoke, or pollution, can cause the eyes to twitch.\n\n9. **Neurological Disorders**: In rare cases, persistent eye twitching can be a symptom of a neurological disorder such as blepharospasm or hemifacial spasm. These conditions typically require medical attention.\n\n10. **Lack of Sleep**: Insufficient sleep can lead to muscle fatigue and twitching, including of the eyelids.\n\n**When to Seek Medical Attention**:\n- If the twitching persists for more than a few weeks\n- If the twitching affects other parts of the face or body\n- If there is swelling, redness, or discharge from the eye\n- If you experience drooping eyelids or difficulty opening the eye\n\nIn most cases, eye twitching is benign and resolves on its own with lifestyle adjustments, such as reducing stress, getting adequate sleep, and limiting caffeine and alcohol intake. However, if you have concerns or if the twitching is persistent and bothersome, it is advisable to consult a healthcare professional.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
